(~900 words)

Interpretability is a cornerstone of modern credit‑risk assessment, particularly as AI models grow in complexity. Regulatory bodies worldwide—including those enforcing Basel III and GDPR—require that automated credit decisions be transparent, auditable, and explainable, ensuring that borrowers, risk managers, and regulators understand how a model arrived at a given decision. While traditional models such as logistic regression or decision trees inherently support explainability, advanced machine learning systems, and especially transformer‑based LLMs, are often opaque. This opacity poses material compliance, fairness, and operational risks. Consequently, integrating explainable AI frameworks into LLM‑based credit‑risk systems has emerged as a critical research frontier.

3.5.1 Why Interpretability Matters in Credit Risk
Because credit decisions determine financial access, consumer outcomes, and regulatory capital requirements, lenders must justify how default probabilities were estimated. Modern regulatory environments demand clarity around:

