3.5.2 SHAP and LIME as Foundational XAI Tools
Two dominant interpretability tools widely adopted in financial modelling are SHAP (Shapley Additive Explanations) and LIME (Local Interpretable Model-Agnostic Explanations). Both aim to approximate local model behavior but do so differently:

LIME constructs a simplified linear model around the neighbourhood of a prediction to identify influential features.
SHAP computes Shapley values to quantify each feature’s contribution according to cooperative game-theory principles.
Salih et al. (2024) provide a deep comparative analysis of SHAP and LIME, emphasising their sensitivity to feature collinearity, model dependence, and the underlying ML model structure. Their findings highlight that SHAP and LIME can become unstable or misleading when inputs exhibit high collinearity—common in financial datasets where macroeconomic variables, borrower characteristics, and behavioural indicators co‑vary.
