2.1 Introduction
Credit risk assessment is a core component of global financial stability, determining whether borrowers—individuals or institutions—can fulfil their financial obligations. Traditional approaches have long depended on structured numerical variables such as income level, credit history, or repayment behaviour. However, modern financial ecosystems produce vast amounts of unstructured, multilingual text, including loan descriptions, analyst comments, financial disclosures, and meeting transcripts. Research demonstrates that this unstructured text contains critical behavioural and contextual signals that enhance credit‑risk modelling accuracy, especially when combined with structured data.

