2.1 Introduction
Credit risk assessment underpins prudent lending, capital allocation and regulatory compliance in banking and non‑bank financial institutions, traditionally relying on structured variables (e.g., repayment history, income, utilisation) and relatively transparent statistical models (e.g., logistic regression, LDA). However, contemporary lending generates abundant unstructured and multilingual text—loan narratives, analyst commentary, earnings call transcripts, regulatory filings and customer communications—that contain actionable risk signals often missed by numeric features alone (Wang, 2024; Wu et al., 2024). The rise of Large Language Models (LLMs) has therefore catalysed a shift from manual feature engineering toward contextual embeddings and generative reasoning that can extract borrower intent, behavioural cues and domain knowledge directly from raw text (Zhao et al., 2024; Lee et al., 2024).

Surveys and systematic mappings show LLMs supporting financial tasks from information extraction to decision support and report generation, yet they also surface unresolved issues—multilingual fragility, explainability, privacy and compliance, and operational efficiency (Lee et al., 2024; Khan, Li and Cao, 2025). Benchmarks designed for finance further reveal that models which perform strongly on English extraction degrade on cross‑lingual reasoning, OCR‑embedded documents and long‑context meeting understanding—patterns with direct implications for global credit scoring (Xie et al., 2024; Peng et al., 2025; Zhu et al., 2026). At the same time, regulators expect transparent, auditable and fair automated decisions, and GDPR introduces hard constraints around data rights and model opacity that current LLMs struggle to satisfy (Feretzakis et al., 2025; Černevičienė and Kabašinskas, 2024).

Against this background, this chapter systematically reviews six pillars: (i) foundations of credit‑risk modelling, (ii) LLMs for credit risk, (iii) multilingual NLP and cross‑lingual transfer, (iv) multilingual/multimodal financial benchmarks, (v) explainability and interpretability (XAI), and (vi) compliance and real‑time deployment concerns. The synthesis exposes gaps that the present research addresses: a multilingual, real‑time, compliance‑aware and explainable LLM framework for credit risk.

Key takeaways: unstructured text materially improves credit default prediction (Wang, 2024; Wu et al., 2024), LLMs expand capability but remain fragile outside English (Xie et al., 2024; Peng et al., 2025), and compliance plus operability constraints must be engineered into any production‑grade solution (Feretzakis et al., 2025; Imai et al., 2024).

2.2 Foundations of Credit Risk Modelling
2.2.1 Traditional models and their limitations
For decades, logistic regression and linear discriminant analysis have been mainstays owing to interpretability, ease of implementation and alignment with supervisory expectations. Yet, recent reviews emphasise that these models struggle with non‑linearities, feature interactions and high‑dimensional signals characteristic of modern credit data and alternative sources (Wang, 2024; Çallı and Coşkun, 2021). Empirically, as datasets scale and borrower heterogeneity increases, linear decision boundaries underfit complex behavioural patterns and macro‑financial dynamics, reducing discrimination and calibration (Wang, 2024; Abikoye and Agorbia‑Atta, 2024).

To address non‑linearity, research moved to machine learning methods (e.g., Random Forests, Gradient Boosting, SVM). A systematic synthesis finds boosted trees (e.g., XGBoost, GBM) often outperform linear baselines in AUC/F1 by capturing interactions and non‑monotonic effects, albeit at the expense of transparency (Abikoye and Agorbia‑Atta, 2024; Wang, 2024). However, even these models largely depend on structured features or manually engineered text attributes (n‑grams, sentiment), leaving untapped the richer semantics of financial narratives (Wu et al., 2024; Teixeira et al., 2023).

2.2.2 The role of unstructured text
Fintech origination platforms, P2P marketplaces and open‑banking workflows routinely collect free‑text loan descriptions and analyst/underwriter notes. Comparative evidence shows that integrating unstructured text with structured covariates significantly improves default prediction, including when the text is generated or transformed by LLMs to highlight salient risk cues (Wu et al., 2024; Teixeira et al., 2023). These gains are consistent with the observation that borrower narratives encode behavioural intent, soft information and context not present in tabular fields (Wang, 2024; Wu et al., 2024).

2.2.3 From traditional ML to transformer‑based NLP
The transition from bag‑of‑words to transformers (e.g., BERT, GPT) enabled models to learn contextual representations from raw text without hand‑crafted features. Surveys chart an evolution from financial PLMs (e.g., FinBERT) to financial LLMs and instruction‑tuned models able to follow prompts for extraction, classification and reasoning (Lee et al., 2025; Li et al., 2023). Nevertheless, as later sections show, finance‑specific advantages in English do not automatically translate to multilingual robustness or compliance‑grade explainability (Xie et al., 2024; Černevičienė and Kabašinskas, 2024).

Implication: foundations motivate an LLM‑augmented pipeline that (a) fuses structured and textual signals, (b) generalises across languages, and (c) satisfies explainability and regulatory constraints (Wang, 2024; Feretzakis et al., 2025).

2.3 LLMs in Credit Risk Assessment
2.3.1 Prompt‑based LLMs
Early deployments adopt prompt engineering to elicit credit‑risk judgements with minimal task‑specific training. Teixeira et al. (2023) integrate Bayesian networks with Labeled Guide Prompting (LGP) to steer GPT‑class models toward coherent report generation; human analysts preferred LGP outputs in 60–90% of blind reviews, and reliability improved compared with unguided prompts (Teixeira et al., 2023; Li et al., 2023). Complementarily, Wu et al. (2024) show that adding ChatGPT‑generated textual assessments to conventional covariates improves default prediction, demonstrating LLMs’ ability to articulate latent risk factors that augment structured features (Wu et al., 2024; Wang, 2024).

These findings indicate that prompt‑based LLMs—despite little fine‑tuning—can enhance risk assessment by surfacing behavioural and contextual cues. Still, such systems inherit the base model’s language coverage and often lack baked‑in controls for bias, privacy and auditability (Lee et al., 2024; Feretzakis et al., 2025).

2.3.2 Fine‑tuned and domain‑adapted LLMs
A second wave fine‑tunes general LLMs or pre‑trains financial LMs for tasks from default prediction to narrative risk reporting. A recent taxonomy of LLM‑driven credit risk organises the field by architecture (GPT/BERT/LLaMA), data types (structured vs. unstructured), explainability mechanisms (e.g., SHAP, LIME, attention, chain‑of‑thought) and applications (credit scoring, compliance, fraud) (Golec and AlabdulJalil, 2025; Khan, Li and Cao, 2025). Beyond classification, end‑to‑end designs incorporate knowledge graphs and RAG to ground generation in verifiable evidence, improving robustness and domain alignment (Li et al., 2026; Zhao et al., 2024). Empirical studies report stability gains across market shifts relative to plain text or purely structured baselines (Li et al., 2026; Abikoye and Agorbia‑Atta, 2024).

Despite progress, two gaps persist. First, most systems are monolingual, primarily English‑trained, limiting deployment in cross‑border lending (Golec and AlabdulJalil, 2025; Lee et al., 2025). Second, interpretability and compliance‑by‑design are commonly treated as afterthoughts, even though lending is a high‑risk, regulated domain (Černevičienė and Kabašinskas, 2024; Feretzakis et al., 2025).

2.3.3 Hybrid pipelines: fusing structured and unstructured signals
Strong results arise when LLM embeddings or LLM‑curated text are fused with structured predictors. Studies on lending portfolios show that text features derived from LLMs add independent lift over numeric variables by capturing intention, soft information and event context (Wu et al., 2024; Teixeira et al., 2023). Surveys suggest practical adoption paths—zero/few‑shot for rapid prototyping, fine‑tuning for scale, and custom FinLLMs for institution‑specific optimisation—balanced against cost, privacy and governance constraints (Li et al., 2023; Lee et al., 2024).

2.3.4 Known limitations and open challenges
Four limitations recur:

Multilingual fragility. Benchmarks show steep drops outside English and under bilingual or code‑switched inputs (Xie et al., 2024; Peng et al., 2025).
Compliance misalignment. LLM opacity complicates GDPR rights (access, rectification, erasure) and audit requirements in automated lending (Feretzakis et al., 2025; Černevičienė and Kabašinskas, 2024).
