2.4.2 Cross‑lingual transfer learning techniques
Two major families of methods show promise in bridging multilingual performance gaps:

(a) Translate‑and‑Test / Translate‑and‑Train (T3L)
The T3L framework reintroduces the classical “translate‑then‑classify” pipeline using modern neural machine translation with soft translations that allow gradients to propagate between translation and classification modules. Jauregi Unanue, Haffari and Piccardi (2023) demonstrate that T3L significantly outperforms naive multilingual fine‑tuning on benchmarks such as XNLI and MLDoc, providing a robust alternative when training data is scarce in target languages. This is highly relevant to credit scoring, where labelled datasets in minority languages are rare.

(b) Language‑adaptive fine‑tuning & contrastive semantics
Liu et al. (2025) show that combining contrastive semantic alignment with language‑adaptive modules improves performance on trilingual financial sentiment analysis. Their results indicate that LLMs benefit from parameter‑efficient, language-specific adapters that capture subtle, domain‑specific patterns across languages (Liu et al., 2025).

